Think of this as a tool to help you clear act 1, just like the pommel strike, cleave, and twin strike it's beta art displays. Obviously it's much worse than those cards, because it will reroll itself randomly in each fight. This forces you to adapt to what it's become, and sometimes it will become a card that is particularly bad in a key fight. It also makes it much harder to build your deck later on, since you don't know if you have enough AOE or not, enough vulnerable/weak or not, just how good the frontloading it provides will be. If you don't know what cards you have in your deck right now, how can you make meaningful decisions about what you still need to add to properly address the concerns of upcoming elites and bosses?

With that being said, snecko has a poor enough early game that you will need some tools like this to help shore up your hallways and elites, and adding a few extra unidentified cards will also help you trigger your snecko soul on turn 1 more consistently, which can be really critical. If you get a fairly good roll considering muddle synergies with high cost cards (clothesline, streamline, roulette, cut through fate, walker claw), or if you hit a good AOE card, then you can attempt to lock it in at a campfire and solidify your deck a bit more. Even if the roll in any given fight isn't perfect, it will help deal damage, and it won't be a skill, so it's at least going to be decent against the act 1 elites, and you can high roll with expensive cards and muddle sometimes. 

Certainly, I think there are better unidentified cards to take that can fill a similar role, like uncommon and rare attack, or 2 or 3 cost. You can also just take a snecko card like snake rake or wide sting and have more stability that way, while also giving some deckbuilding direction. I don't like ??? C attack very much, but if it's the best tool I can find, I will use it. You definitely shouldn't be taking this after fulfilling your front loaded damage needs in early act 1.

For the record, I do think that snecko would be significantly improved if you could identify a card as a free action at each campfire, giving you more opportunities to solidify your deck and create a direction, without having to lose out on upgrades. I personally think that muddle is in a reasonable place, take all the expensive cards isn't exactly the deepest gameplay incentive, but it works well enough, and is very flavorful for snecko. The dice cards are probably one of the biggest areas of possible improvement, nearly all of them are terrible even if you roll fairly well on average, and offer little to no utility. Something like concentrate for hermit that makes it more possible to roll well would be an improvement (I know Lucky exists, but that one like 1 rare card and a shop relic only). Maybe you could have a scaling modifier (think strength or dexterity) where a flat number gets added to all your dice rolls (sort of like modifiers in D&D). A power called loaded that modifiers all your dice rolls by 2 (3) for 1 energy?

I think I mentioned it last time that unid'd cards came up, but I think in my ideal world unid'd cards would just pick three cards from the relevant pool when they're generated (and tell you which cards upfront) rather than use the whole pool. And instead of id'ing there'd be the opportunity to reroll one of those cards. Captures the intended feel of snecko without being impossible to build around, and creates an incentive to take the card if one of the things it can turn into is really good. Of course, I recognize that may or may not be difficult to implement.
